# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pspace
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] In computational complexity theory, **generalized geography** is a well-known PSPACE-complete problem.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Geography is a children's game, where players take turns naming cities from anywhere in the world.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Each city chosen must begin with the same letter that ended the previous city name.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The game begins with an arbitrary starting city and ends when a player loses because they are unable to continue.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] To visualize the game, a directed graph can be constructed whose nodes are each cities of the world.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] An arrow is added from node *N*1 to node *N*2 if and only if the city labeling *N*2 starts with the letter that ending the name of the city labeling node *N*1.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] In other words, we draw an arrow from one city to another if the first can lead to the second according to the game rules.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Each alternate edge in the directed graph corresponds to each player (for a two player game).
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The first player unable to extend the path loses.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] An illustration of the game (containing some cities in Michigan) is shown in the figure below.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] In a generalized geography (GG) game, we replace the graph of city names with an arbitrary directed graph.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The following graph is an example of a generalized geography game.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] We define *P*1 as the player moving first and *P*2 as the player moving second and name the nodes *N*1 to *N**n*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] In the above figure, *P*1 has a winning strategy as follows: *N*1 points only to nodes *N*2 and *N*3.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Thus *P*1's first move must be one of these two choices.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] *P*1 chooses *N*2 (if *P*1 chooses *N*3, then *P*2 will choose *N*9 as that is the only option and *P*1 will lose).
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Next *P*2 chooses *N*4 because it is the only remaining choice.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] *P*1 now chooses *N*5 and *P*2 subsequently chooses *N*3 or *N*7.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Regardless of *P*2's choice, *P*1 chooses *N*9 and *P*2 has no remaining choices and loses the game.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The problem of determining which player has a winning strategy in a generalized geography game is PSPACE-complete.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Let GG = { ⟨*G*, *b*⟩ | *P*1 has a winning strategy for the generalized geography game played on graph *G* starting at node *b* }; to show that GG ∈ PSPACE, we present a polynomial-space recursive algorithm determining which player has a winning strategy.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Construct a list of all nodes reachable from *n*start by one edge: *n*1, *n*2, ..., *n**i*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Remove *n*start and all edges connected to it from *G* to form *G*1.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] If all of these calls return *accept*, then no matter which decision *P*1 makes, *P*2 has a strategy to win, so return *reject*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Otherwise (if one of the calls returns *reject*) *P*1 has a choice that will deny any successful strategies for *P*2, so return *accept*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] It is in PSPACE because the only non-obvious polynomial workspace consumed is in the recursion stack.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The space consumed by the recursion stack is polynomial because each level of recursion adds a single node to the stack, and there are at most *n* levels, where *n* is the number of nodes in *G*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] This is essentially equivalent to a depth-first search.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The following proof is due to David Lichtenstein and Michael Sipser.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] To establish the PSPACE-hardness of GG, we can reduce the FORMULA-GAME problem (which is known to be PSPACE-hard) to GG in polynomial time (P).
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] In brief, an instance of the FORMULA-GAME problem consists of a quantified Boolean formula φ = ∃*x*1 ∀*x*2 ∃*x*3 ...*Qxk*(ψ) where *Q* is either ∃ or ∀.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The game is played by two players, *Pa* and *Pe*, who alternate choosing values for successive *xi*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] *Pe* wins the game if the formula ψ ends up *true*, and *Pa* wins if ψ ends up *false*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The formula ψ is assumed to be in conjunctive normal form.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] In this proof, we assume that the quantifier list starts and ends with the existential qualifier, ∃, for simplicity.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Note that any expression can be converted to this form by adding dummy variables that do not appear in ψ.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] By constructing a graph *G* like the one shown above, we will show any instance of FORMULA-GAME can be reduced to an instance of Generalized Geography, where the optimal strategy for *P1* is equivalent to that of *Pe*, and the optimal strategy for *P2* is equivalent to that of *Pa*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The left vertical chain of nodes is designed to mimic the procedure of choosing values for variables in FORMULA-GAME.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Each diamond structure corresponds to a quantified variable.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Players take turns deciding paths at each branching node.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Because we assumed the first quantifier would be existential, *P*1 goes first, selecting the left node if *x*1 is *true* and the right node if *x*1 is *false*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Each player must then take forced turns, and then *P2* chooses a value for *x*2.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] These alternating assignments continue down the left side.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] After both players pass through all the diamonds, it is again *P*1 's turn, because we assumed that the last quantifier is existential.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] *P*1 has no choice but to follow the path to the right side of the graph.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] When the play gets to the right side of the graph, it is similar to the end of play in the formula game.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Recall that in the formula game, *Pe* wins if ψ is *true*, while *Pa* wins if ψ is *false*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The right side of the graph guarantees that *P1* wins if and only if *Pe* wins, and that *P*2 wins if and only if *Pa* wins.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] First we show that *P*2 always wins when *Pa* wins.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] If ψ is *false*, there exists an unsatisfying clause.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] *P*2 will choose an unsatisfying clause to win.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Then when it is *P*1's turn he must choose a literal in that clause chosen by *P*2.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Since all the literals in the clause are *false*, they do not connect to previously visited nodes in the left vertical chain.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] This allows *P*2 to follow the connection to the corresponding node in a diamond of the left chain and select it.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] However, *P*1 is now unable to select any adjacent nodes and loses.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Now we show that *P*1 always wins when *Pe* wins.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] If ψ is *true*, every clause in the right side of the graph contains a *true* literal.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Then *P*1 chooses the literal that is *true*.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] And because it is *true*, its adjacent node in the left vertical node has already been selected, so *P*2 has no moves to make and loses.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Generalized geography is PSPACE-complete, even when played on planar graphs.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The following proof is from theorem 3 of.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Since planar GG is a special case of GG, and GG is in PSPACE, so planar GG is in PSPACE.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] It remains to show that planar GG is PSPACE-hard.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] This can be proved by showing how to convert an arbitrary graph into a planar graph, such that a game of GG played on this graph will have the same outcome as on the original graph.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] In order to do that, it's only necessary to eliminate all the edge crossings of the original graph.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] We draw the graph such that no three edges intersect at a point, and no pair of crossing edges can both be used in the same game.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] This is not possible in general, but is always possible for the graph constructed from a FORMULA-GAME instance; for example we could have only the edges from clause vertices involved in crossings.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] The result is a planar graph, and the same player can force a win as in the original graph: if a player chooses to move "up" from V in the transformed game, then both players must continuing moving "up" to W or lose immediately.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] So moving "up" from V in the transformed game simulates the move V→W in the original game.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] If V→W is a winning move, then moving "up" from V in the transformed game is also a winning move, and vice versa.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Thus, the game of GG played on the transformed graph will have the same outcome as on the original graph.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] This transformation takes time that is a constant multiple to the number of edge intersections in the original graph, thus it takes polynomial time.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] GG played on planar bipartite graphs with maximum degree 3 is still PSPACE-complete, by replacing the vertices of degree higher than 3 with a chain of vertices with degree at most 3.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] If one player uses any of the entrances to this construction, the other player chooses which exit will be used.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Also the construction can only be traversed once, because the central vertex is always visited.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Hence this construction is equivalent to the original vertex.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] A variant of GG is called **edge geography**, where after each move, the edge that the player went through is erased.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] This is in contrast to the original GG, where after each move, the vertex that the player used to be on is erased.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] In this view, the original GG can be called **Vertex Geography**.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] This can be proved used the same construction that was used for vertex geography.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] One may also consider playing either Geography game on an undirected graph (that is, the edges can be traversed in both directions).
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Fraenkel, Scheinerman, and Ullman show that **undirected vertex geography** can be solved in polynomial time, whereas **undirected edge geography** is PSPACE-complete, even for planar graphs with maximum degree 3.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] If the graph is bipartite, then Undirected Edge Geography is solvable in polynomial time.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] Given that GG is PSPACE-complete, no polynomial time algorithm exists for optimal play in GG unless P = PSPACE.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] However, it may not be as easy to prove the complexity of other games because certain games (such as chess) contain a finite number of game positions — making it hard (or impossible) to formulate a mapping to a PSPACE-complete problem.
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] In spite of this, the complexity of certain games can still be analyzed by generalization (e.g., to an *n* × *n* board).
[src:pspace/generalized-geography] See the references for a proof for generalized Go, as a corollary of the proof of the completeness of GG.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] In computational complexity theory, a decision problem is **PSPACE-complete** if it can be solved using an amount of memory that is polynomial in the input length (polynomial space) and if every other problem that can be solved in polynomial space can be transformed to it in polynomial time.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] The problems that are PSPACE-complete can be thought of as the hardest problems in PSPACE, the class of decision problems solvable in polynomial space, because a solution to any one such problem could easily be used to solve any other problem in PSPACE.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] Problems known to be PSPACE-complete include determining properties of regular expressions and context-sensitive grammars, determining the truth of quantified Boolean formulas, step-by-step changes between solutions of combinatorial optimization problems, and many puzzles and games.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] A problem is defined to be PSPACE-complete if it can be solved using a polynomial amount of memory (it belongs to PSPACE) and every problem in PSPACE can be transformed in polynomial time into an equivalent instance of the given problem.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] The PSPACE-complete problems are widely suspected to be outside the more famous complexity classes P (polynomial time) and NP (non-deterministic polynomial time), but that is not known.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] The transformations that are usually considered in defining PSPACE-completeness are polynomial-time many-one reductions, transformations that take a single instance of a problem of one type into an equivalent single instance of a problem of a different type.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] However, it is also possible to define completeness using Turing reductions, in which one problem can be solved in a polynomial number of calls to a subroutine for the other problem.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] It is not known whether these two types of reductions lead to different classes of PSPACE-complete problems.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] Other types of reductions, such as many-one reductions that always increase the length of the transformed input, have also been considered.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] A version of the Berman–Hartmanis conjecture for PSPACE-complete sets states that all such sets look alike, in the sense that they can all be transformed into each other by polynomial-time bijections.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] Given a regular expression R , determining whether it generates every string over its alphabet is PSPACE-complete.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] The first known PSPACE-complete problem was the word problem for deterministic context-sensitive grammars.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] In the word problem for context-sensitive grammars, one is given a set of grammatical transformations which can increase, but cannot decrease, the length of a sentence, and wishes to determine if a given sentence could be produced by these transformations.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] In 1970, Savitch's theorem showed that PSPACE is closed under nondeterminism, implying that even non-deterministic context-sensitive grammars are in PSPACE.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] A standard PSPACE-complete problem, used in many other PSPACE-completeness results, is the quantified Boolean formula problem, a generalization of the Boolean satisfiability problem.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] Reconfiguration problems concern the connectivity of a state space of solutions to a combinatorial problem.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] For instance, testing whether two 4-colorings of a graph can be connected to each other by moves that change the color of one vertex at a time, maintaining at each step a valid 4-coloring, is PSPACE-complete, even though the same problem for 3-colorings can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] The quantified Boolean formula problem can be interpreted as a game by two players, a verifier and a falsifier.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] A quantified formula is true if and only if the verifier has a winning strategy.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] Similarly, the problem of determining the winner or loser of many other combinatorial games turns out to be PSPACE-complete.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] Examples of games that are PSPACE-complete (when generalized so that they can be played on an $n\times n$ board) are the games Hex and Reversi.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] Some other generalized games, such as chess, checkers (draughts), and Go are EXPTIME-complete because a game between two perfect players can be very long, so they are unlikely to be in PSPACE.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] But they will become PSPACE-complete if a polynomial bound on the number of moves is enforced.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] It is also possible for puzzles played by a single player to be PSPACE-complete.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] These often can be interpreted as reconfiguration problems, and include the solitaire games Rush Hour, Mahjong, Atomix and Sokoban, and the mechanical computer Turing Tumble.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] PSPACE-completeness is based on complexity as a function of the input size n , in the limit as n grows without bound.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] Puzzles or games with a bounded number of positions such as chess on a conventional $8\times 8$ board cannot be PSPACE-complete, because they could be solved in constant time and space using a very large lookup table.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] To formulate PSPACE-complete versions of these games, they must be modified in a way that makes their number of positions unbounded, such as by playing them on an $n\times n$ board instead.
[src:pspace/pspace-complete] In some cases, such as for chess, these extensions are artificial.
[src:pspace/pspace] In computational complexity theory, **PSPACE** is the set of all decision problems that can be solved by a Turing machine using a polynomial amount of space.
[src:pspace/pspace] It turns out that allowing the Turing machine to be nondeterministic does not add any extra power.
[src:pspace/pspace] Because of Savitch's theorem, ${\mathsf {NPSPACE}}$ is equivalent to ${\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ , because a deterministic Turing machine can simulate a nondeterministic Turing machine while roughly squaring the amount of space, and squaring takes polynomials to (bigger) polynomials.
[src:pspace/pspace] Also, the complements of all problems in ${\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ are also in ${\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ , meaning that ${\mathsf {coPSPACE}}={\mathsf {PSPACE}}$ .
[src:pspace/pspace] From the third line, it follows that both in the first and in the second line, at least one of the set containments must be strict, but it is not known which.
[src:pspace/pspace] It is widely suspected that all are strict.
[src:pspace/pspace] The containments in the third line are both known to be strict.
[src:pspace/pspace] The first follows from direct diagonalization (the space hierarchy theorem, NL ⊂ NPSPACE) and the fact that PSPACE = NPSPACE via Savitch's theorem.
[src:pspace/pspace] The second follows simply from the space hierarchy theorem.
[src:pspace/pspace] The hardest problems in PSPACE are the PSPACE-complete problems.
[src:pspace/pspace] See PSPACE-complete for examples of problems that are suspected to be in PSPACE but not in NP.
[src:pspace/pspace] The class PSPACE is closed under operations union, complementation, and Kleene star.
[src:pspace/pspace] An alternative characterization of PSPACE is the set of problems decidable by an alternating Turing machine in polynomial time, sometimes called APTIME or just AP.
[src:pspace/pspace] A logical characterization of PSPACE from descriptive complexity theory is that it is the set of problems expressible in second-order logic with the addition of a transitive closure operator.
[src:pspace/pspace] A full transitive closure is not needed; a commutative transitive closure and even weaker forms suffice.
[src:pspace/pspace] It is the addition of this operator that (possibly) distinguishes PSPACE from PH.
[src:pspace/pspace] A major result of complexity theory is that PSPACE can be characterized as all the languages recognizable by a particular interactive proof system, the one defining the class IP.
[src:pspace/pspace] In this system, there is an all-powerful prover trying to convince a randomized polynomial-time verifier that a string is in the language.
[src:pspace/pspace] It should be able to convince the verifier with high probability if the string is in the language, but should not be able to convince it except with low probability if the string is not in the language.
[src:pspace/pspace] PSPACE can be characterized as the quantum complexity class QIP.
[src:pspace/pspace] PSPACE is also equal to PCTC, problems solvable by classical computers using closed timelike curves, as well as to BQPCTC, problems solvable by quantum computers using closed timelike curves.
[src:pspace/pspace] A language *B* is *PSPACE-complete* if it is in PSPACE and it is PSPACE-hard, which means for all *A* ∈ PSPACE, $A\leq _{\text{P}}B$ , where $A\leq _{\text{P}}B$ means that there is a polynomial-time many-one reduction from *A* to *B*.
[src:pspace/pspace] PSPACE-complete problems are of great importance to studying PSPACE problems because they represent the most difficult problems in PSPACE.
[src:pspace/pspace] Finding a simple solution to a PSPACE-complete problem would mean we have a simple solution to all other problems in PSPACE because all PSPACE problems could be reduced to a PSPACE-complete problem.
[src:pspace/pspace] An example of a PSPACE-complete problem is the quantified Boolean formula problem (usually abbreviated to **QBF** or **TQBF**; the **T** stands for "true").
[src:pspace/reconfiguration] In discrete mathematics and theoretical computer science, **reconfiguration** problems are computational problems involving reachability or connectivity of state spaces.
[src:pspace/reconfiguration] Here, a state space is a discrete set of configurations of a system or solutions of a combinatorial problem, called states, together with a set of allowed moves linking one state to another.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] In computational complexity theory, **Savitch's theorem**, proved by Walter Savitch in 1970, gives a relationship between deterministic and non-deterministic space complexity.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] In other words, if a nondeterministic Turing machine can solve a problem using $f(n)$ space, a deterministic Turing machine can solve the same problem in the square of that space bound.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] Although it seems that nondeterminism may produce exponential gains in time (as formalized in the unproven exponential time hypothesis), Savitch's theorem shows that it has a markedly more limited effect on space requirements.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] That is, for any oracle, replacing every "Turing machine" with "oracle Turing machine" would still result in a theorem.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] The proof relies on an algorithm for STCON, the problem of determining whether there is a path between two vertices in a directed graph, which runs in $O\left((\log n)^{2}\right)$ space for n vertices.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] The basic idea of the algorithm is to solve recursively a somewhat more general problem, testing the existence of a path from a vertex s to another vertex t that uses at most k edges, for a parameter k given as input.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] STCON is a special case of this problem where k is set large enough to impose no restriction on the paths (for instance, equal to the total number of vertices in the graph, or any larger value).
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] To test for a k -edge path from s to t , a deterministic algorithm can iterate through all vertices u , and recursively search for paths of half the length from s to u and from u to t .
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] Because each recursive call halves the parameter k , the number of levels of recursion is $\lceil \log _{2}n\rceil$ .
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] Each level requires $O(\log n)$ bits of storage for its function arguments and local variables: k and the vertices s , t , and u require $\lceil \log _{2}n\rceil$ bits each.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] The total auxiliary space complexity is thus $O\left((\log n)^{2}\right)$ .
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] The input graph is considered to be represented in a separate read-only memory and does not contribute to this auxiliary space bound.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] Alternatively, it may be represented as an implicit graph.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] Although described above in the form of a program in a high-level language, the same algorithm may be implemented with the same asymptotic space bound on a Turing machine.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] This algorithm can be applied to an implicit graph whose vertices represent the configurations of a nondeterministic Turing machine and its tape, running within a given space bound $f(n)$ .
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] The edges of this graph represent the nondeterministic transitions of the machine, s is set to the initial configuration of the machine, and t is set to a special vertex representing all accepting halting states.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] In this case, the algorithm returns true when the machine has a nondeterministic accepting path, and false otherwise.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] The number of configurations in this graph is $O(2^{f(n)})$ , from which it follows that applying the algorithm to this implicit graph uses space $O(f(n)^{2})$ .
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] Thus by deciding connectivity in a graph representing nondeterministic Turing machine configurations, one can decide membership in the language recognized by that machine, in space proportional to the square of the space used by the Turing machine.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] That is, the languages that can be recognized by deterministic polynomial-space Turing machines and nondeterministic polynomial-space Turing machines are the same.
[src:pspace/savitch-s-theorem] This follows directly from the fact that the square of a polynomial function is still a polynomial function.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] In computational complexity theory, the language **TQBF** is a formal language consisting of the **true quantified Boolean formulas**.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] A (fully) quantified Boolean formula is a formula in quantified propositional logic (also known as Second-order propositional logic) where every variable is quantified (or bound), using either existential or universal quantifiers, at the beginning of the sentence.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Such a formula is equivalent to either true or false (since there are no free variables).
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] If such a formula evaluates to true, then that formula is in the language TQBF.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] It is also known as **QSAT** (Quantified SAT).
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] In computational complexity theory, the **quantified Boolean formula problem** (**QBF**) is a generalization of the Boolean satisfiability problem in which both existential quantifiers and universal quantifiers can be applied to each variable.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Put another way, it asks whether a quantified sentential form over a set of Boolean variables is true or false.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF is the canonical complete problem for PSPACE, the class of problems solvable by a deterministic or nondeterministic Turing machine in polynomial space and unlimited time.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Given the formula in the form of an abstract syntax tree, the problem can be solved easily by a set of mutually recursive procedures which evaluate the formula.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Such an algorithm uses space proportional to the height of the tree, which is linear in the worst case, but uses time exponential in the number of quantifiers.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Provided that MA ⊊ PSPACE, which is widely believed, QBF cannot be solved, nor can a given solution even be verified, in either deterministic or probabilistic polynomial time (in fact, unlike the satisfiability problem, there's no known way to specify a solution succinctly).
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] It can be solved using an alternating Turing machine in linear time, since AP = PSPACE, where AP is the class of problems alternating machines can solve in polynomial time.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] When the seminal result IP = PSPACE was shown (see interactive proof system), it was done by exhibiting an interactive proof system that could solve QBF by solving a particular arithmetization of the problem.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF formulas have a number of useful canonical forms.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For example, it can be shown that there is a polynomial-time many-one reduction that will move all quantifiers to the front of the formula and make them alternate between universal and existential quantifiers.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] There is another reduction that proved useful in the IP = PSPACE proof where no more than one universal quantifier is placed between each variable's use and the quantifier binding that variable.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This was critical in limiting the number of products in certain subexpressions of the arithmetization.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] A fully quantified Boolean formula can be assumed to have a very specific form, called prenex normal form.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] It has two basic parts: a portion containing only quantifiers and a portion containing an unquantified Boolean formula usually denoted as $\displaystyle \phi$ .
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] where every variable falls within the scope of some quantifier.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] By introducing dummy variables, any formula in prenex normal form can be converted into a sentence where existential and universal quantifiers alternate.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The second sentence has the same truth value but follows the restricted syntax.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Assuming fully quantified Boolean formulas to be in prenex normal form is a frequent feature of proofs.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] There is a simple recursive algorithm for determining whether a QBF is in TQBF (i.e. is true).
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] If the formula contains no quantifiers, we can just return the formula.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For every quantifier in the initial QBF, the algorithm makes two recursive calls on only a linearly smaller subproblem.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This gives the algorithm an exponential runtime O(2*n*).
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Within each invocation of the algorithm, it needs to store the intermediate results of computing A and B.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Every recursive call takes off one quantifier, so the total recursive depth is linear in the number of quantifiers.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Formulas that lack quantifiers can be evaluated in space logarithmic in the number of variables.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The initial QBF was fully quantified, so there are at least as many quantifiers as variables.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This makes the TQBF language part of the PSPACE complexity class.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Despite the PSPACE-completeness of QBF, many solvers have been developed to solve these instances (This is analogous to the situation with SAT, the single existential quantifier version; even though it is NP-complete, it is still possible to solve many SAT instances heuristically).
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The case where there are only 2 quantifiers, known as 2QBF, has received special attention.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The QBF solver competition QBFEVAL has been running more-or-less annually since 2004; solvers are required to read instances in QDIMACS format and either the QCIR or QAIGER formats.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] High-performing QBF solvers generally use QDPLL (a generalization of DPLL) or CEGAR.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF solvers can be applied to planning (in artificial intelligence), including safe planning; the latter is critical in applications of robotics.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF solvers can also be applied to bounded model checking as they provide a shorter encoding than would be needed for a SAT-based solver.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The evaluation of a QBF can be seen as a two-player game between a player who controls existentially quantified variables and a player who controls universally quantified variables.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This makes QBFs suitable for encoding reactive synthesis problems.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Similarly, QBF solvers can be used to model adversarial games in game theory.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For example, QBF solvers can be used to find winning strategies for games of geography, which can then be automatically played interactively.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF solvers can be used for formal equivalence checking, and can also be used to synthesize Boolean functions.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The Stochastic Satisfiability problem (known as SSAT) is an extension of TQBF that adds a randomizing R quantifier, views universal quantification as minimization, and existential quantification as maximization, and asks, whether the probability represented by the formula exceeds a given threshold.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] QBF can be also extended to have Henkin quantifiers.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The TQBF language serves in complexity theory as the canonical PSPACE-complete problem.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Being PSPACE-complete means that a language is in PSPACE and that the language is also PSPACE-hard.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The algorithm above shows that TQBF is in PSPACE.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Showing that TQBF is PSPACE-hard requires showing that any language in the complexity class PSPACE can be reduced to TQBF in polynomial time.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This means that, for a PSPACE language L, whether an input x is in L can be decided by checking whether $f(x)$ is in TQBF, for some function f that is required to run in polynomial time (relative to the length of the input).
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Proving that TQBF is PSPACE-hard, requires specification of f.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] So, suppose that L is a PSPACE language.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This means that L can be decided by a polynomial space deterministic Turing machine (DTM).
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] We know that *T* = *O*(exp(*n*k)) for some *k*, where *n* is the length of the input, because this bounds the total number of possible configurations of the relevant DTM.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Of course, it cannot take the DTM more steps than there are possible configurations to reach $c_{\mathrm {accept} }$ unless it enters a loop, in which case it will never reach $c_{\mathrm {accept} }$ anyway.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] At this stage of the proof, we have already reduced the question of whether an input formula w (encoded, of course, in $c_{\text{start}}$ ) is in L to the question of whether the QBF $\phi _{c_{\text{start}},c_{\text{accept}},T}$ , i.e., $f(w)$ , is in TQBF.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The remainder of this proof proves that f can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For $t=1$ , computation of $\phi _{c_{1},c_{2},t}$ is straightforward—either one of the configurations changes to the other in one step or it does not.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Since the Turing Machine that our formula represents is deterministic, this presents no problem.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] For $t>1$ , computation of $\phi _{c_{1},c_{2},t}$ involves a recursive evaluation, looking for a so-called "middle point" $m_{1}$ .
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This converts the question of whether $c_{1}$ can reach $c_{2}$ in t steps to the question of whether $c_{1}$ reaches a middle point $m_{1}$ in $t/2$ steps, which itself reaches $c_{2}$ in $t/2$ steps.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] The answer to the latter question of course gives the answer to the former.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Now, t is only bounded by T, which is exponential (and so not polynomial) in the length of the input.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Additionally, each recursive layer virtually doubles the length of the formula.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] (The variable $m_{1}$ is only one midpoint—for greater t, there are more stops along the way, so to speak.) So the time required to recursively evaluate $\phi _{c_{1},c_{2},t}$ in this manner could be exponential as well, simply because the formula could become exponentially large.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This problem is solved by universally quantifying using variables $c_{3}$ and $c_{4}$ over the configuration pairs (e.g., $\{(c_{1},m_{1}),(m_{1},c_{2})\}$ ), which prevents the length of the formula from expanding due to recursive layers.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This version of the formula can indeed be computed in polynomial time, since any one instance of it can be computed in polynomial time.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Thus, $\forall L\in {\mathsf {PSPACE}},L\leq _{p}\mathrm {TQBF}$ , so TQBF is PSPACE-hard.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] Together with the above result that TQBF is in PSPACE, this completes the proof that TQBF is a PSPACE-complete language.
[src:pspace/true-quantified-boolean-formula] This construction can be run in logspace, meaning that TQBF is PSPACE-complete in he sense of logspace many-one reduction.
